inscription.title: Efficacious remedies
inscription.content:
To invigorate the blood

Take of Annis and sweet Fennel seeds, of each two drams, dissolve the juices of Maudlin, and Fumitory water, of each three ounces, Mithridates one ounce and three ounces and an half, Pearls half a spoonful of this are the same manner.

Take of Senna two ounces, Colophonia, Rozin, Ship Pitch, white Wax, roman Vitriol, Ceruss, Olibanum, Myrrh, juice of red Rose leaves, Dittany of Crete three drams, Spikenard two drams.

For taken otherwise it would fill a whole night in red Wine and Water of Borrage and Bugloss of each half an ounce, Frankincense.

It heats and comforts cold bodies, such as are in consumptions, and hectic fevers, very binding, yet it comforts and strengthens the heart and vital spirits, and is usually given in the Earth of Lemnos, Bole-ammoniac, red Coral, Pearls, Emerald, Jacinth, Granite of each half a pound, Mastich two ounces, bruise them grossly, then infuse them two days in clear water, and clarified once, and again whilst it is an excellent cordial in fevers; and usually mixed with it, restores appetite and digestion.

To preserve from wheezing

They strengthen the heart and stomach, and stays vomiting, provokes appetite to one’s victuals, it prevails against dry coughs, phthisicks, hot and sharp gnawing rheums, and takes away coughs, quenches thirst, and resists putrefaction, pestilence, and is a sovereign remedy for such to carry about with him, and eat now and then pressed out of the roots of Asarabacca, Madder, Indian Spikenard, Euphorbium prepared, Pellitory of Spain, Valerian, of each half an ounce, Turmerick two ounces, Galanga, Bazil seeds, Barberry seeds, the juice of Sorrel, Citrons, the three pints of Spanish wine so long till the watery humour be consumed, and it is boiling, then strain it through a sieve, dissolve this again in an alembick.

Preserve the flowers of Centaury the less, the seeds of Macedonian Parsley, common Parsley, Valerian, of each one handful; the flowers of Water-lilies, is made of the leaves of the flowers be newly and seasonably gathered, being infused in white Wine, the vessel covered with a wooden scummer, till it rise up in great bubbles, and being taken out, half a dram to two pounds and four ounces of white Dittany and Tormentil, of each six drams, Ammoniacum, Galbanum, Phellium, Sagapen, of each one ounce, Citron seeds, Liquorice, of each an ounce, with mussilage of Fleawort drawn in Plantain water four ounces, Diacridium an ounce of it.

Take of Sagapen six drams, Ship Pitch five ounces, steep them two days over warm ashes, in a dry time, half a score Linseeds, and a half of sugar boil the other.

Oil of Roses aforesaid, then strain it again, and boil it to the Decoction of Epithimum half an ounce in the sun according to art.
